sections.text:
Each Lot shall be used solely as a residential property or for purposes incidental to residential use. No Lot shall be used for any commercial, business, industrial, or manufacturing purpose, or for transient or hotel-type occupancy, except as specifically permitted by this Declaration or the Rules of Conduct. No commercial signage, equipment, or vehicles shall be displayed on any Lot.

Notwithstanding the foregoing, the following uses are permitted:

\- Reasonable home-based business conducted entirely within a residence and not involving retail customer visits or commercial traffic;

\- Rental of a Lot as a residence, subject to the restrictions in Article IX;

\- Professional services (consulting, counseling, etc.) conducted within a residence, provided no signage or customer visits are visible from the street;

\- Leasing of a portion of a Lot (such as a guest house) to a Tenant, subject to compliance with Article IX.

Nothing in this Section shall be construed to prohibit reasonable accommodations for persons with disabilities as required by the Fair Housing Act (42 U.S.C. \&#x00A7; 3601 et seq.), the Americans with Disabilities Act, the Texas Fair Housing Act (Tex. Prop. Code Chapter 301), or applicable law. Owners and residents with disabilities may request reasonable accommodations of Association rules and reasonable structural modifications to their dwellings by submitting a written request to the Board.

In-home health care services, in-home childcare services, and visits by personal care attendants are permitted uses incidental to residential use and shall not be deemed violations of this Section or of the single-family residential use restriction.

Any home-based business must be approved in advance by the Board and must comply with all applicable zoning and building codes of the City of Austin.

Home-based businesses shall comply with the following standards: (a) no more than two (2) client or customer visits per day; (b) no exterior signage, advertising, or displays indicating a business is conducted on the premises; (c) no on-site employees other than persons residing in the dwelling; (d) no commercial vehicles, equipment, or inventory visible from neighboring properties or the street; (e) the business shall not generate noise, odor, traffic, or parking demand materially greater than typical residential use; and (f) the business shall comply with all applicable City of Austin zoning and licensing requirements. The Board may require cessation of any home-based business that, in its reasonable judgment, materially disrupts the residential character of the community.

No signs of any kind may be erected or maintained on any Lot, except the following:

\- One residential address sign not exceeding three square feet;

\- "For Sale" or "For Rent" signs not exceeding six square feet and removed within seven days of sale or rental;

\- Security system signs identifying the security company;

\- One flagpole as permitted in Section 26 below;

\- Other signs as specifically approved by the Board.

Residential rental of a Lot is permitted subject to the requirements of this Article IX and the Rules of Conduct. The following uses are prohibited:

\- Short-term rentals of less than one hundred eighty (180) days, except as provided in Section 2;

\- Commercial or business use of a Lot;

\- Transient occupancy or hotel-type use;

\- Any use that creates a nuisance or is otherwise prohibited by this Declaration.

Before assessing any fine, the Board shall provide written notice to the Owner specifying the alleged violation and providing the Owner an opportunity to cure the violation within a reasonable time period, not to exceed thirty (30) days, unless a longer cure period is established in the Rules of Conduct. The notice shall include the following information:

\- A detailed description of the alleged violation;

\- The specific provision of this Declaration, the Bylaws, or the Rules of Conduct allegedly violated;

\- The date and time of the alleged violation;

\- The identity of any witnesses;

\- A statement that the Owner has a right to a hearing before the Board;

\- A copy of the relevant provision and any Rules of Conduct;

\- The deadline for curing the violation;

\- The consequences of failure to cure, including potential fines.

If an Owner fails to cure a violation within the specified time period, the Board may assess a fine as provided in Section 4 below or may pursue other remedies.

Before any dispute between Owners, or between an Owner and the Association, may be submitted to arbitration or litigation, the parties shall first attempt to resolve the dispute through mediation as provided in the Bylaws. The specific mediation procedures, including mediator selection, process, cost allocation, and time limits, are established in the Bylaws.

Mediation shall be conducted by a qualified mediator agreed upon by the parties, or if the parties cannot agree within fifteen (15) days, appointed by the Board from a list of mediators maintained by the Travis County Dispute Resolution Center. Mediation shall be completed within sixty (60) days of the mediator's appointment. The costs of mediation shall be shared equally by the parties; each party shall bear its own attorney's fees. No party may file a lawsuit or demand arbitration regarding any dispute subject to this Section until mediation has been attempted and has concluded without resolution.

The Association, through its Board of Directors, is empowered and shall have the authority to enforce all covenants, conditions, and restrictions contained in this Declaration. The Board may pursue enforcement through any means available under Texas law, including but not limited to:

\- Issuing notice and opportunity to cure;

\- Assessing fines as provided in Article XII, Section 4;

\- Filing suit for injunctive relief to prevent or remedy violations;

\- Pursuing liens and foreclosure for unpaid assessments as provided in Article IV.

The Association may also seek attorney's fees and costs from violators as permitted by Texas law.

The Board shall establish and maintain Rules of Conduct implementing and supplementing the provisions of this Declaration. The Rules of Conduct shall include detailed procedures and standards regarding:

\- Architectural and landscaping standards;

\- Permitted and prohibited uses;

\- Pet and animal standards;

\- Noise, nuisance, and disturbance standards;

\- Trash and waste management;

\- Complaint and enforcement procedures;

\- Fines and penalties;

\- Assessment collection procedures.

The Rules of Conduct shall be adopted by Board resolution and provided to all Members.

Every Owner has the right to inspect and receive copies of Association records under Texas Property Code \&#x00A7; 209.007. The specific procedures for requesting and obtaining copies of Association records, including timelines, fees, and format options, are set forth in the Bylaws. The Association's duty to provide records applies only to existing books and records. The Association is not obligated to create a new document, prepare a summary of information, or compile and report data.

Records exempt from disclosure include the following:

\- Information relating to violations of rules and regulations not yet publicly disclosed;

\- Information regarding the Association's legal, investigative, or settlement strategies;

\- Attorney-client communications and work product;

\- Information relating to pending litigation;

\- Financial records relating to Owners, Tenants, or other individuals;

\- Information that would compromise the security of the Properties or individuals;

\- Private information of Members and non-member residents.
